{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599774"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:58:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:58:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15588"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15588"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0,0.09,0,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70194"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8279"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55658"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"688"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19996"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70194"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents with fatigue, weight gain, and cold intolerance. Her medical history includes a brief period of anxiety, palpitations, and heat intolerance eight months ago. Laboratory testing reveals elevated anti-thyroid peroxidase antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical progression of Hashimoto thyroiditis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypothyroidism only","Hyperthyroidism only","Hypothyroid phase then hyperthyroid phase","No change in thyroid function","Hyperthyroid phase then hypothyroid phase"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHashimoto thyroiditis typically follows a biphasic course. Initially, patients may experience a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperthyroid phase\u003C/strong\u003E due to inflammation-mediated destruction of thyroid follicles, causing release of stored thyroid hormones. This is followed by a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothyroid phase\u003C/strong\u003E as the autoimmune destruction of thyroid tissue progresses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is incorrect that patients experience \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperthyroidism only\u003C/strong\u003E, as the condition usually involves both phases. \u003Cstrong\u003ENo change in thyroid function\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as thyroid function is significantly affected. The progression from \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothyroid to hyperthyroid\u003C/strong\u003E phase does not occur, as the destruction of thyroid tissue leads to permanent hypothyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis is confirmed by the presence of anti-thyroid peroxidase (anti-TPO) and anti-thyroglobulin antibodies, with ultrasound typically showing a heterogeneous, hypoechoic thyroid gland.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hashimoto thyroiditis typically progresses from a transient hyperthyroid phase to permanent hypothyroidism due to autoimmune destruction of thyroid tissue.","The initial hyperthyroid phase occurs due to inflammation-mediated release of stored thyroid hormones.","Anti-thyroid peroxidase and anti-thyroglobulin antibodies are characteristic of Hashimoto thyroiditis."],"references":["Klubo-Gwiezdzinska J, Wartofsky L. Hashimoto thyroiditis: an evidence-based guide to etiology, diagnosis and treatment. Pol Arch Intern Med. 2022 Mar 30;132(3):16222. doi: 10.20452/pamw.16222. Epub 2022 Mar 3. PMID: 35243857; PMCID: PMC9478900.","Caturegli P, De Remigis A, Chuang K, Dembele M, Iwama A, Iwama S. Hashimoto\u0027s thyroiditis: celebrating the centennial through the lens of the Johns Hopkins hospital surgical pathology records. Thyroid. 2013 Feb;23(2):142-50. doi: 10.1089/thy.2012.0554. PMID: 23151083; PMCID: PMC3569966.","Patil N, Rehman A, Anastasopoulou C, et al. Hypothyroidism. [Updated 2024 Feb 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519536/","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55658"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15588"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55658"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T08:11:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T08:20:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8279"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70194"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"